'''''The Eraser''''' is the debut solo album by [[Thom Yorke]] of the English alternative rock band [[Radiohead]], released on 10 July 2006 on the independent label [[XL Recordings]]. It was produced by [[Nigel Godrich]].

The album comprises [[electronic music]] Yorke recorded during Radiohead's 2004 hiatus and between their 2005 rehearsals. The lyrics express Yorke's political concerns; "[[Harrowdown Hill]]" was written about the death of [[David Kelly (weapons expert)|David Kelly]], a [[whistleblower]] who allegedly committed suicide after telling a reporter that the British government had falsely identified weapons of mass destructions in Iraq. The album artwork, by [[Stanley Donwood]], was inspired by the [[King Canute and the waves|legend of King Canute failing to command the ocean]], which Yorke likened to government attitudes towards [[climate change]].

''The Eraser'' debuted at number three on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and number two on the American [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. It was named one of the best albums of 2006 by the ''[[NME]]'', ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and the ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'', and was nominated for the 2006 [[Mercury Music Prize]] and the 2007 [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album]].

The album produced two singles, "[[Analyse (Thom Yorke song)|Analyse]]" and "Harrowdown Hill". It was followed in the same year by a B-sides EP, ''[[Spitting Feathers]]'', and in 2009 a [[remix album]], ''[[The Eraser Rmxs]].'' In 2010, to perform the album live, Yorke formed [[Atoms for Peace (band)|Atoms for Peace]] with musicians including Godrich and [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] bassist [[Flea (musician)|Flea]].

==Background and recording==
[[File:Yorkelatitude.JPG|thumb|In July 2009, Yorke played a solo performance at the [[Latitude Festival]] in England, performing ''Eraser'' material.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Thom Yorke debuts new song at Latitude festival - video|url = http://www.nme.com/news/radiohead/46193|accessdate = 2015-05-04}}</ref>]]
In 2004, after finishing the tour for their sixth album ''[[Hail to the Thief]]'' (2003)'','' Yorke's band [[Radiohead]] went on a year-long hiatus. Yorke began recording ''The Eraser'' with Radiohead producer [[Nigel Godrich]] in late 2004 and continued work throughout 2005 between Radiohead rehearsals.<ref name="Rolling_Stone">{{cite web |url = http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/radioheads-frontman-goes-solo-20060615 |title = Radiohead's Thom Yorke on Going Solo |accessdate = 16 July 2006 |author = Fricke, David |authorlink = David Fricke |date = 1 June 2006 |publisher = ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' }}</ref> He told [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]: "I've been in the band since we left school and never dared do anything on my own ... It was like, 'Man, I've got to find out what it feels like,' you know?"<ref name=":5">{{cite web |url = http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/6402-thom-yorke/ |title = Interview: Thom Yorke |accessdate = 6 April 2007 |author = Plagenhoef, Scott |date = 16 August 2006 |publisher = ''[[Pitchfork Media]]'' }}</ref> The album was recorded in Radiohead's Oxford studio, Godrich's studio in [[Covent Garden]], London, and Yorke's home.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|title = Interview with Radiohead's Thom Yorke|url = http://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/jun/18/9|website = The Guardian|accessdate = 2015-05-03|first = Craig|last = McLean}}</ref>

Yorke wanted to "approach and engage with computers and not a lot else, and yet still have lots of life and energy in the music."<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url = http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/radiohead-retooled/article711010/|title = Radiohead retooled|date = June 14, 2006|accessdate = 3 January 2015|website = |publisher = The Globe and Mail|last = Evert-Green|first = Robert}}</ref> To generate ideas, he cut and pasted clips at random from Radiohead's library of original [[sampling (music)|samples]].<ref name=":0" /> To create the title track, he sampled piano chords played by Radiohead guitarist [[Jonny Greenwood]] and cut them into a new order.<ref name="Rolling_Stone"/> "And it Rained All Night" contains an unrecognisable sample from "The Gloaming" (from ''Hail to the Thief''), and "[[Black Swan (song)|Black Swan]]" samples a recording made by Radiohead guitarist [[Ed O'Brien]] and drummer [[Philip Selway]] in 2000.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title = Radiohead's Frontman Goes Solo|url = http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/radioheads-frontman-goes-solo-20060615#ixzz3Z64zcB7H|accessdate = 2015-05-03}}</ref> Yorke said "[[Harrowdown Hill]]" was "kicking around" during the ''Hail to the Thief'' recording sessions in 2002, but that "there was no way that was going to work with the band."<ref name=":1" />

Yorke initially intended to create instrumental tracks without vocals,<ref name=":0" /> but made them songs at the encouragement of Godrich, who said "because it was predominantly electronic, I had a really good excuse to make his voice dry and loud."<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|title = Thom Yorke, free agent|url = http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jun/28/entertainment/et-yorke28|newspaper = Los Angeles Times|date = June 28, 2006|access-date = 2015-05-03|issn = 0458-3035|language = en-US|first = Ann|last = Powers}}</ref> Yorke found it difficult to write lyrics to loops of music, saying he could not "react spontaneously and differently every time";<ref name=":0" /> to finish the lyrics, he translated the music to guitar and piano and generated new musical components in the process.<ref name=":0" />

== Music and lyrics ==
The ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' described ''The Eraser'' as "an insidious collection of skittery beats and pattery rhythms and minimal [[post-rock]]isms".<ref name=":2" /> The ''[[LA Times]]'' described it as "an evocative portrait of life made slippery by urban sprawl, murky political alliances and global warming ... with the blips and bleeps of Yorke's laptop excursions coalescing into soulful, politically charged songs."<ref name=":3" /> Pitchfork described it as "glitchy, sour, feminine, brooding".<ref name="pitchfork">{{Cite web|title = Thom Yorke: The Eraser|url = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/9183-the-eraser/|accessdate = 2015-05-03}}</ref> Citing inspiration from the 1997 [[Bj<U+00F6>rk]] album ''[[Homogenic]],'' Yorke said the album was designed to be heard in an "isolated space ''<U+2013>'' on headphones, or stuck in traffic."<ref name=":3" />

[[David Fricke]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' felt the album's lyrics have an "emotional and pictorial directness, rare for Yorke".<ref name="Rolling_Stone" /> Yorke said the album title was inspired by "these huge elephants that we have in the room at the moment, in the West, and people are desperately trying to erase them from public consciousness."<ref name=":0" /> According to the ''[[The Globe and Mail|Globe and Mail]]'', "The Clock", influenced by [[Arabic music]], is a "gliding, droning song about losing control while pretending 'that you are still in charge'."<ref name=":0" /> "[[Analyse (Thom Yorke song)|Analyse]]" was inspired by a [[power outage|blackout]] Yorke experienced in his hometown [[Oxford]]: "The houses were all dark, with candlelight in the windows, which is obviously how it would have been when they were built. It was beautiful."<ref name="Rolling_Stone" />

"Harrowdown Hill" was written about [[David Kelly (weapons expert)|David Kelly]], a [[whistleblower]] who allegedly committed suicide after telling a reporter that the British government had falsely identified [[weapon of mass destruction|weapons of mass destruction]] in Iraq. His body was found in the Harrowdown Hill woods near Yorke's former school in Oxfordshire.<ref name=":3" /> According to the ''Globe and Mail'', the song resembles a love song with a sense of "menace" and "grim political showdown".<ref name="H">{{cite web |url = http://www.ateaseweb.com/2006/06/14/thom-yorke-interview-in-globe-and-mail/|title = Radiohead retooled|accessdate = 14 June 2006|author = Everett-Green, Robert|date = 14 June 2006|publisher = ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''}}</ref> Yorke was uncomfortable about the subject matter and conscious of Kelly's grieving family, but felt that "not to write it would perhaps have been worse."<ref name=":0" /> In an interview with the ''Observer'', he said it was "the most angry song" he'd ever written.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://observer.guardian.co.uk/omm/story/0,,1795948,00.html |title = All Messed Up |accessdate = 18 June 2006 |author = Mclean, Craig |date = 18 June 2006 |publisher = ''[[The Observer|Observer Music Monthly]]'' }}</ref>

==Artwork and packaging==
[[Image:EraserSleeve.jpg|thumb|250px|Part of ''London Views,'' the album artwork created by Stanley Donwood.]]

The ''Eraser'' cover artwork, a [[linocut]] by [[Stanley Donwood]] titled ''London Views'', depicts a figure standing before London destroyed by flood, in imitation of [[King Canute and the waves|King Canute failing to command the ocean]].<ref name=":3" /> The artwork was inspired by the 2004 [[Boscastle flood of 2004|Boscastle flood]]<ref>{{cite web |url = http://latest-art.co.uk/features/?id=4 |title = Got It Covered |accessdate = 13 December 2007 |author = Meacher, Colette |year = 2006 |publisher = ''Latest Art'' }}</ref> and an article by the environmentalist [[Jonathan Porritt]] comparing the British government's attitude to [[climate change]] to Canute.<ref name=":3" /> The album is packaged as a single large foldout containing the CD; Donwood and Yorke wanted to avoid using plastic.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Donwood Dresses Up Thom Yorke Solo Album|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58124/donwood-dresses-up-thom-yorke-solo-album|accessdate = 2015-05-03}}</ref>

== Release ==
On 11 May 2006, Yorke posted a link to [http://www.theeraser.net theeraser.net] on the official Radiohead website. Two days later, Yorke released a press release announcing ''The Eraser'', writing: "I have been itching to do something like this for ages. It was fun and quick to do ... Yes, it's a record! No, it's not a Radiohead record." He emphasised that Radiohead were not splitting up and that the album was made "with their blessing".<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|title = Eraserhead: Thom Yorke Goes Solo - Stereogum|url = http://www.stereogum.com/2602/eraserhead_thom_yorke_goes_solo/news/|accessdate = 2015-05-03}}</ref>

''The Eraser'' was released on July 11, 2006<ref name=":4"/> by the independent label [[XL Recordings]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Radiohead singer confirms solo album but denies rumours of split|url = http://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/may/16/radiohead.popandrock|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-05-03|first = Paul|last = Arendt}}</ref> Yorke said he chose the label because "it's very mellow. There's no corporate ethic. All [major labels are] like that. Stupid little boys' games ''<U+2013>'' especially really high up."<ref name=":5"/> The album ''<nowiki/>''debuted at number three in the UK albums chart and stayed in the top 100 for ten weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Official Charts Company|url = http://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/THE%20ERASER/|website = www.officialcharts.com|accessdate = 2015-05-03}}</ref> In the United States, it debuted at number two on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling over 90,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Thom Yorke's No Match For Chamillionaire, Kelly Clarkson In Billboard Race|url = http://www.mtv.com/news/1536652/thom-yorkes-no-match-for-chamillionaire-kelly-clarkson-in-billboard-race/|website = MTV News|accessdate = 2015-05-03}}</ref> The album [[internet leak|leaked online]] a month before release; Yorke said he regretted not releasing the album as a download beforehand.<ref name="paste">{{Cite web|title = Thom Yorke: Dancing in the Dark|url = http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2006/08/thom-yorke.html|accessdate = 2015-05-04|publisher = ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''|last = D'amico|first = Pier Nicola|date = 2006-08-08}}</ref>

''The'' ''Eraser'' produced two singles: "Harrowdown Hill" on August 21<ref>{{Cite web|title = Harrowdown Hill|url = http://web.archive.org/web/20061022143651/http://www.xlrecordings.com/thomyorke/release/~harrowdown-hill-cd/|date = 2006-10-22|accessdate = 2015-05-04}}</ref> and "Analyse" on November 6.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Thom Yorke's favourite Radiohead tune revealed|url = http://www.nme.com/news/thom-yorke/24831|accessdate = 2015-05-04}}</ref> It was followed in the same year by a B-sides EP, ''[[Spitting Feathers]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|title = Spitting Feathers - Thom Yorke {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards {{!}} AllMusic|url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/spitting-feathers-mw0000457704|website = AllMusic|accessdate = 2015-05-03}}</ref> and in 2009 by ''[[The Eraser Rmxs]],'' an album of remixes by various artists.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Thom Yorke: The Eraser Rmxs|url = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12612-the-eraser-rmxs/|accessdate = 2015-05-02}}</ref>

In 2010, to perform ''The Eraser'' live, Yorke formed [[Atoms for Peace (band)|Atoms for Peace]] with musicians including Godrich and [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] bassist [[Flea (musician)|Flea]] and played eight North American shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/blogs/alternate-take/q-a-thom-yorke-on-atoms-for-peaces-mechanistic-new-album-20121105|title=Q&A: Thom Yorke on Atoms for Peace's 'Mechanistic' New Album|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=November 5, 2012|accessdate=Feb 18, 2013}}</ref>

