On the review aggregator site [[Metacritic]], ''The Eraser'' has a score of 76/100, indicating "generally favorable reviews".<ref name="metacritic">{{cite web |url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-eraser/thom-yorke |title = The Eraser by Thom Yorke |accessdate = 1 October 2008 |authorlink = |date = |publisher = [[MetaCritic]]}}</ref>

Louis Patterson of the ''[[NME]]'' praised Yorke's vocals and likened the album to Radiohead's 2000 album ''[[Kid A]],'' writing: "Some will mourn its lack of viscera; its coldness; its reluctance to rock. But it<U+2019>s yet another revealing glimpse into Yorke's cryptic inner-world, and one that has the courage not to hide its political message in code."<ref name="nme">{{cite web|last = Patterson|first = Louis|title = Thom Yorke: The Eraser|publisher = ''[[NME]]''|url = http://www.nme.com/reviews/thom-yorke/7973|accessdate = 3 February 2009|date = 7 July 2006}}</ref> [[Rob Sheffield]] of ''Rolling Stone'' also likened it to ''Kid A'' and said: "These aren't Radiohead songs, or demos for Radiohead songs. They're something different, something we haven't heard before ... it's intensely beautiful, yet it explores the kind of emotional turmoil that makes the angst of [Radiohead albums] ''[[OK Computer]]'' or ''[[The Bends]]'' sound like kid stuff."<ref name="rolling">{{cite web|last = Sheffield|first = Rob|title = Thom Yorke: The Eraser|publisher = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''|url = http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-eraser-20060710#ixzz3Z6dBf7cy|accessdate = 13 February 2009|date = 26 June 2006}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' wrote: "''The Eraser'' isn<U+2019>t a masterpiece, but it<U+2019>s much more than solo-project divergence. Yorke has stayed focused and created a tight album that draws on its predecessors without being held to or afraid of them."<ref name="Popmatters">{{Cite web|title = Thom Yorke: The Eraser|url = http://www.popmatters.com/review/thom-yorke-the-eraser/|accessdate = 2015-05-04|website = Popmatters|last = Corberlake|first = Justin}}</ref>

In the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'', [[Alexis Petridis]] wrote that the album "offers a plethora of low-key delights", but "you can't help imagining what it might have sounded like if Yorke had turned it over to Radiohead."<ref name="petridis">{{cite web|last = Petridis|first = Alexis|title = Thom Yorke, The Eraser|publisher = ''[[The Guardian]]''|url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2006/jul/07/popandrock.shopping2|accessdate = 16 March 2009|date = 7 July 2006}}</ref> Pitchfork wrote that ''The Eraser'' is "strikingly beautiful and thuddingly boring in maddeningly equal measure."<ref name="pitchfork"/> The [[The Village Voice|''Village Voice'']]''<nowiki/>'' praised Yorke's vocals, but found that his "without the hooks of his inspirations or [Radiohead's] density, the results offer pleasantries where they could provoke profound unpleasantries."<ref name="village">{{Cite web|title = The Android You're Looking For|url = http://www.villagevoice.com/2006-07-04/music/the-android-you-re-looking-for/|accessdate = 2015-05-04|first = Barry|last = Walters|publisher = ''[[The Village Voice|Village Voice]]''}}</ref>

''The Eraser'' was named the 15th best album of 2006 by the ''NME'',<ref>{{Cite web|title = A decade in music - 50 best albums of 2006|url = http://www.nme.com/photos/a-decade-in-music-50-best-albums-of-2006/161055#/photo/38|website = NME.COM|accessdate = 2015-05-04}}</ref> the 30th by the ''Observer'',<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Observer's best albums of the year|url = http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2006/dec/09/omms50bestalbumsoftheyea|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-05-04|first = Caspar Llewellyn|last = Smith}}</ref> and the 34th by ''Rolling Stone.''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Rolling Stone<U+2018>s Best Albums Of <U+2019>06 - Stereogum|url = http://www.stereogum.com/4165/rolling_stones_best_albums_of_06/franchises/list/|accessdate = 2015-05-04}}</ref> It was nominated for the 2006 [[Mercury Prize]]<ref>{{Cite web |url = http://www.nme.com/news/nme/24216|work = NME|accessdate = 10 June 2009|date = 5 September 2006|title = Arctic Monkeys win 2006 Mercury Music Prize}}</ref> and the 2007 [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album]].<ref name="Grammy1992">{{cite news|url = http://www.nytimes.com/1992/01/09/arts/grammy-short-list-many-for-a-few.html?pagewanted=1|title = Grammy Short List: Many For a Few|first = Jon|last = Pareles|date = January 9, 1992|accessdate = April 30, 2010|work = The New York Times|publisher = The New York Times Company}}</ref>

